## Diagnosing "Too Many Connections"

```sql
-- 1. See all active connections right now
SELECT pid, usename, application_name, state, query_start, state_change, query
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE datname = 'postgres'
ORDER BY query_start DESC;

-- 2. Count connections by state
SELECT state, COUNT(*) FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE datname = 'postgres' GROUP BY state;
-- idle = held but not doing anything (connection leak)
-- active = running a query
-- idle in transaction = transaction started but not committed (dangerous)

-- 3. Kill a specific connection
SELECT pg_terminate_backend(pid) FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE pid = [PID];

-- 4. Kill all idle connections (emergency fix)
SELECT pg_terminate_backend(pid)
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE datname = 'postgres' AND state = 'idle' AND pid != pg_backend_pid();
```

### Common causes and fixes

| Cause | Fix |
|---|---|
| Using port 5432 in serverless (each invocation holds a connection) | Switch to port 6543 |
| Drizzle/Prisma not using connection pooling | Add `?pgbouncer=true` or set `prepare: false` |
| Database client not closed after use | Use try/finally to close, or use connection pool with max |
| Too many concurrent Netlify functions | Set `max_connections` in pool config, or upgrade compute |
| pgBouncer pool exhausted | Increase pool_size in Supavisor dashboard settings |

